# Lesson 1 – Navigation & Filesystem Basics

## pwd

Displays the absolute path of the current working directory.

### Syntax

```bash
pwd
```

Example

```bash
/home/hamad/linux-practice
```

---

## ls

Lists files and directories.

```bash
ls
```

---

## ls -a

Displays all files including hidden files.

```bash
ls -a
```

Hidden files begin with a dot (`.`).

Example

```text
.bashrc
.profile
.git
```

---

## ls -l

Displays detailed file information.

```bash
ls -l
```

Example

```text
drwxr-xr-x 2 hamad hamad 4096 Jun 30 18:20 projects
```

Information displayed:

* File type
* Permissions
* Owner
* Group
* Size
* Modification date
* Name

---

### Understanding Linux Permissions

Example

```text
drwxr-xr-x
```

| Part | Meaning   |
| ---- | --------- |
| d    | Directory |
| r    | Read      |
| w    | Write     |
| x    | Execute   |

Permissions are divided into:

```
Owner | Group | Others
```

Example

```
rwx r-x r-x
```

---

## cd

Changes the current directory.

Examples

```bash
cd projects

cd ..

cd ~

cd /
```

---

## mkdir

Creates directories.

```bash
mkdir projects
```

Create multiple directories

```bash
mkdir logs config backups
```

---

## touch

Creates empty files.

```bash
touch README.md
```

Multiple files

```bash
touch notes.txt app.conf todo.txt
```

---

## tree

Displays the directory tree.

```bash
tree
```

Example

```text
.
├── config
├── logs
├── README.md
└── scripts
```

