# Lesson 2 – Working with Paths

## Absolute Path

Starts from the root directory (`/`).

Example

```bash
cd /home/hamad/linux-practice/projects
```

---

## Relative Path

Starts from the current directory.

Example

```bash
cd projects/project1
```

---

## Special Directories

### Current Directory

```
.
```

Examples

```bash
find .

./script.sh
```

---

### Parent Directory

```
..
```

Example

```bash
cd ..
```

---

### Home Directory

```
~
```

Example

```bash
cd ~
```

---

# Lesson 3 – File Operations

## cp

Copies files.

```bash
cp source.txt destination.txt
```

Copy a directory recursively

```bash
cp -r projects backups
```

---

## mv

Moves or renames files.

Move

```bash
mv notes.txt Documents/
```

Rename

```bash
mv old.txt new.txt
```

---

## rm

Deletes a file.

```bash
rm notes.txt
```

---

## rmdir

Deletes an empty directory.

```bash
rmdir temp
```

---

## rm -r

Deletes a directory recursively.

```bash
rm -r projects
```

---

## rm -rf

Deletes recursively without confirmation.

```bash
rm -rf folder
```

⚠️ Use with extreme caution.

---

# Lesson 4 – Viewing & Inspecting Files

## cat

Displays the entire contents of a file.

```bash
cat file.txt
```

Create a file from the terminal

```bash
cat > notes.txt
```

Append text

```bash
cat >> notes.txt
```

---

## less

Views large files page by page.

```bash
less logfile.log
```

Useful shortcuts:

* Space → Next page
* b → Previous page
* /text → Search
* q → Quit

---

## head

Displays the first 10 lines.

```bash
head file.txt
```

Custom number

```bash
head -20 file.txt
```

---

## tail

Displays the last 10 lines.

```bash
tail file.txt
```

Follow live updates

```bash
tail -f application.log
```

---

## wc

Counts:

* Lines
* Words
* Characters

```bash
wc file.txt
```

Examples

```bash
wc -l file.txt

wc -w file.txt

wc -c file.txt
```

---

## file

Identifies the file type.

```bash
file image.png
```

Example

```text
image.png: PNG image data
```

---

# Lesson 5 – Searching & Filtering

## find

Searches for files and directories.

Search by name

```bash
find . -name "*.txt"
```

Search only directories

```bash
find . -type d
```

Search only files

```bash
find . -type f
```

---

## grep

Searches inside files.

```bash
grep "error" logfile.log
```

Ignore case

```bash
grep -i linux notes.txt
```

Recursive search

```bash
grep -r "TODO" .
```

Show line numbers

```bash
grep -n "main" app.py
```

---

## Pipes

Send the output of one command into another.

```bash
command1 | command2
```

Examples

```bash
ls | less

cat file.txt | grep Linux

history | grep ssh
```

---

# Lesson 6 – Text Processing

## cut

Extracts columns from text.

```bash
cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd
```

---

## sort

Sorts lines alphabetically.

```bash
sort names.txt
```

Reverse

```bash
sort -r names.txt
```

Numeric

```bash
sort -n scores.txt
```

---

## uniq

Removes consecutive duplicate lines.

```bash
uniq file.txt
```

Count duplicates

```bash
uniq -c file.txt
```

Usually combined with sort

```bash
sort file.txt | uniq
```

---

## awk

Powerful text-processing tool.

Print the first column

```bash
awk '{print $1}' file.txt
```

Custom delimiter

```bash
awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd
```

---

## sed

Stream editor for searching and replacing text.

Replace the first occurrence

```bash
sed 's/Linux/Ubuntu/' file.txt
```

Replace all occurrences

```bash
sed 's/Linux/Ubuntu/g' file.txt
```

